/* CCSP :: content/quiz1.js — CCSP Domain 1 question bank (100 items). */
window.CCSP = window.CCSP || {}; CCSP.questions = CCSP.questions || [];
CCSP.questions.push.apply(CCSP.questions, [{"id":"D1-001","domain":1,"obj":"1.1","diff":"easy","q":"A finance team spins up 40 new virtual machines during quarter-end close and releases them a week later, paying only for the hours consumed. Which essential NIST cloud characteristic does this most directly illustrate?","options":["Rapid elasticity","Resource pooling","Broad network access","Measured service"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Rapid elasticity</strong> — the capacity scaled out to meet a spike and then contracted, appearing effectively unlimited and appropriated in any quantity at any time, which is the definition of rapid elasticity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Resource pooling</b>: describes the provider serving many tenants from a shared, multi-tenant pool with location abstraction, not the customer's ability to scale up and down.</span><span class='qd'><b>Broad network access</b>: refers to reaching services over standard networks from diverse client devices, not to scaling capacity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Measured service</b>: covers metering and billing of usage; while pay-per-hour touches metering, the scenario's defining action is scaling capacity out and back in.</span>"},{"id":"D1-002","domain":1,"obj":"1.1","diff":"easy","q":"An organization contracts a firm to help it negotiate, aggregate, and manage the use of multiple cloud services on its behalf, adding a unified billing and access portal. In the NIST reference model, what role is this firm playing?","options":["Cloud provider","Cloud broker","Cloud auditor","Cloud carrier"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Cloud broker</strong> — a broker manages use, performance, and delivery of cloud services and negotiates relationships between consumers and providers, often adding intermediation and aggregation value such as a unified portal.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud provider</b>: makes the service available; the firm is not operating the underlying services, it is intermediating access to others'.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud auditor</b>: performs independent assessment of controls and performance, not service aggregation or billing consolidation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud carrier</b>: provides the connectivity and transport between consumer and provider, not brokerage of services.</span>"},{"id":"D1-003","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"easy","q":"A company deploys an application to a managed runtime where the provider maintains the operating system, middleware, and language runtime, while the company supplies only its code and data. Which service category is this?","options":["IaaS","SaaS","PaaS","FaaS"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>PaaS</strong> — Platform as a Service gives the customer a managed application platform (OS, middleware, runtime patched by the provider) onto which they deploy their own code and data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>IaaS</b>: would require the customer to manage the operating system and middleware themselves on provisioned VMs, which contradicts the provider maintaining the OS.</span><span class='qd'><b>SaaS</b>: delivers a finished application the customer merely configures; here the customer still writes and deploys code.</span><span class='qd'><b>FaaS</b>: is a narrower event-driven function model; the scenario describes a general managed runtime for the company's application, the classic PaaS pattern rather than discrete functions.</span>"},{"id":"D1-004","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"easy","q":"Several hospitals in the same region jointly build and share a cloud environment governed by common healthcare-privacy requirements, restricting membership to organizations in that sector. Which deployment model is this?","options":["Public cloud","Hybrid cloud","Private cloud","Community cloud"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Community cloud</strong> — infrastructure shared by several organizations with common concerns (mission, security, compliance) is by definition a community cloud.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Public cloud</b>: is open to the general public and not restricted to a specific community with shared requirements.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hybrid cloud</b>: combines two or more distinct deployment models bound by technology enabling portability; the scenario is one shared environment, not a composition.</span><span class='qd'><b>Private cloud</b>: is provisioned for a single organization's exclusive use, whereas here multiple hospitals share it.</span>"},{"id":"D1-005","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"easy","q":"A cloud administrator needs an application to authenticate to a database without any human logging in and without embedding a long-lived password in code. Which IAM construct is designed for this?","options":["Service account with managed credentials","Privileged user account","Break-glass account","Guest account"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Service account with managed credentials</strong> — service (non-human) identities exist precisely so applications and workloads can authenticate programmatically, ideally with short-lived, platform-managed credentials.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Privileged user account</b>: is a human administrative identity subject to interactive login and MFA, not intended for automated app-to-service authentication.</span><span class='qd'><b>Break-glass account</b>: is an emergency human account used only when normal access fails, not for routine application authentication.</span><span class='qd'><b>Guest account</b>: represents limited external human access and is entirely unsuitable for a workload identity.</span>"},{"id":"D1-006","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"A security architect must guarantee that decommissioned tenant data on shared, multi-tenant storage is rendered unrecoverable, but the provider will not allow physical destruction or degaussing of the disks. Which sanitization technique is most appropriate?","options":["Single-pass overwrite","Cryptographic erasure (crypto-shredding)","Physical shredding","Degaussing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Cryptographic erasure (crypto-shredding)</strong> — when data was encrypted and you destroy the keys, the ciphertext becomes unrecoverable; this is the go-to method in shared cloud storage where physical destruction is impossible.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Single-pass overwrite</b>: is unreliable in the cloud because you cannot guarantee you overwrote every physical location holding your data on multi-tenant, abstracted storage.</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical shredding</b>: is explicitly ruled out and would also destroy other tenants' data on shared media.</span><span class='qd'><b>Degaussing</b>: is likewise disallowed here and is ineffective against SSDs, besides being a provider-only physical operation.</span>"},{"id":"D1-007","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"An organization adopts a network model in which no user or workload is trusted by default, every request is authenticated and authorized based on identity and context, and access is granted per-session with least privilege. Which concept is being implemented?","options":["Perimeter (castle-and-moat) security","Network address translation","Zero trust architecture","Air-gapping"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Zero trust architecture</strong> — the defining tenets are 'never trust, always verify,' continuous per-request authentication and authorization using identity and context, and least-privilege per-session access.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Perimeter (castle-and-moat) security</b>: assumes internal traffic is trusted once inside the boundary, the opposite of zero trust.</span><span class='qd'><b>Network address translation</b>: rewrites IP addresses and is not an access-control trust model.</span><span class='qd'><b>Air-gapping</b>: physically isolates a network; it is a form of trust-by-isolation, not the continuous verification model described.</span>"},{"id":"D1-008","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"medium","q":"A retailer wants to run steady baseline workloads in its own on-premises private cloud but 'burst' to a public cloud during holiday peaks, keeping the two integrated so workloads can move between them. Which deployment model and property does this describe?","options":["Multi-cloud emphasizing vendor diversity","Public cloud emphasizing broad network access","Community cloud emphasizing shared compliance","Hybrid cloud enabling cloud bursting and portability"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Hybrid cloud enabling cloud bursting and portability</strong> — combining a private and a public cloud bound together so workloads can shift (bursting) is the textbook hybrid pattern, and workload mobility relies on portability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Multi-cloud emphasizing vendor diversity</b>: means using several public providers; the scenario mixes deployment models (private + public), which is hybrid, not merely multiple vendors.</span><span class='qd'><b>Public cloud emphasizing broad network access</b>: ignores the private on-premises component central to the scenario.</span><span class='qd'><b>Community cloud emphasizing shared compliance</b>: involves multiple organizations with common concerns, which is not what a single retailer bursting to public cloud describes.</span>"},{"id":"D1-009","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"medium","q":"During procurement, a legal team insists the contract allow the organization to retrieve all of its data and metadata and fully exit the provider at end of term, leaving nothing behind. Which shared consideration is this requirement chiefly about?","options":["Reversibility","Interoperability","Portability","Resiliency"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Reversibility</strong> — reversibility is the ability to retrieve all assets and artifacts and have the provider delete them upon termination, i.e., cleanly undo the outsourcing relationship.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Interoperability</b>: is the ability of systems to work together and exchange information, not the ability to exit a provider.</span><span class='qd'><b>Portability</b>: is the ability to move data or workloads between environments; it supports exit but the specific requirement to retrieve everything and have the provider purge it is reversibility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Resiliency</b>: concerns the ability to withstand and recover from faults, unrelated to contract exit.</span>"},{"id":"D1-010","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"medium","q":"A team wants to run the same application container image unchanged across a developer laptop, a private cloud, and two different public clouds. Which enabling technology most directly delivers this workload portability?","options":["Serverless functions","Containers and container orchestration","Blockchain","Confidential computing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Containers and container orchestration</strong> — containers package an application with its dependencies into a standardized, portable image that runs consistently across any compliant host, and orchestration schedules them uniformly across environments.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Serverless functions</b>: are often tightly coupled to a specific provider's event and runtime model, which tends to reduce cross-cloud portability rather than guarantee it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Blockchain</b>: is a distributed ledger technology and has nothing to do with packaging an application image for portable execution.</span><span class='qd'><b>Confidential computing</b>: protects data in use via trusted execution environments; it addresses confidentiality, not portable deployment of an image.</span>"},{"id":"D1-011","domain":1,"obj":"1.1","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP is explaining why cloud economics differ from traditional IT. Which characteristic most directly enables the shift from large up-front capital expenditure to usage-based operating expenditure?","options":["On-demand self-service","Resource pooling","Measured service","Broad network access"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Measured service</strong> — metering of consumption is what allows providers to charge per unit of use, converting fixed capital costs into variable operating costs billed to actual usage.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>On-demand self-service</b>: lets a consumer provision without human interaction; it speeds provisioning but is not the metering that underpins pay-per-use billing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Resource pooling</b>: improves provider efficiency through multi-tenancy but does not itself define the billing model.</span><span class='qd'><b>Broad network access</b>: concerns reachability over the network, unrelated to cost structure.</span>"},{"id":"D1-012","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"hard","q":"A hypervisor flaw could allow code in one guest VM to read memory belonging to another guest on the same physical host. What class of threat does this represent, and which control most directly reduces its likelihood?","options":["Data remanence; use crypto-shredding","Man-in-the-middle; enforce TLS everywhere","Denial of service; enable autoscaling","VM escape / guest breakout; keep the hypervisor patched and hardened"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>VM escape / guest breakout; keep the hypervisor patched and hardened</strong> — a guest reading another guest's memory via a hypervisor defect is a VM escape (breakout of tenant isolation); the primary mitigation is rigorous hypervisor patching and hardening to eliminate such flaws.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data remanence; use crypto-shredding</b>: addresses residual data on decommissioned media, not live cross-VM memory access through the hypervisor.</span><span class='qd'><b>Man-in-the-middle; enforce TLS everywhere</b>: protects data in transit on the network; the attack here is local memory isolation failure, which TLS does not touch.</span><span class='qd'><b>Denial of service; enable autoscaling</b>: is the wrong threat class entirely; the issue is confidentiality/isolation, not availability.</span>"},{"id":"D1-013","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"hard","q":"An architect evaluates AI/ML services offered by a cloud provider and is asked to identify the security consideration most unique to these services compared with traditional compute. Which is the best answer?","options":["Training-data confidentiality and model/data poisoning risk","Metered billing accuracy","Broad network access from mobile devices","Standard patch cadence for the OS"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Training-data confidentiality and model/data poisoning risk</strong> — AI/ML introduces distinctive risks: sensitive training data exposure, model inversion, and poisoning of data or the model itself, which are not present in ordinary compute.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Metered billing accuracy</b>: applies to any measured cloud service and is not unique to AI/ML security.</span><span class='qd'><b>Broad network access from mobile devices</b>: is a generic cloud characteristic, not an AI-specific security concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Standard patch cadence for the OS</b>: is a baseline hygiene practice common to all systems and does not capture what is distinctive about AI/ML.</span>"},{"id":"D1-014","domain":1,"obj":"1.1","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is a foundational building block of cloud computing that abstracts physical hardware so multiple isolated guests can share one physical server?","options":["Geofencing","Virtualization","Tokenization","Federation"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Virtualization</strong> — virtualization abstracts physical compute, memory, storage, and network so multiple isolated virtual guests can run on shared hardware; it is a core building block of cloud.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Geofencing</b>: restricts access based on geographic location and is a network-security control, not a hardware-abstraction building block.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tokenization</b>: substitutes sensitive values with non-sensitive tokens for data protection, unrelated to hardware sharing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Federation</b>: links identity across trust domains; it is an IAM concept, not a compute-abstraction technology.</span>"},{"id":"D1-015","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"A team must protect cryptographic keys for a regulated workload such that key material is generated and stored in tamper-resistant hardware and never leaves it in plaintext. Which component best meets this need?","options":["Software key vault on a general-purpose VM","Certificate signing request","Hardware Security Module (HSM)","Reverse proxy"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Hardware Security Module (HSM)</strong> — an HSM is dedicated, tamper-resistant hardware that generates, stores, and uses keys internally so key material never leaves in plaintext, satisfying strict key-protection requirements.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Software key vault on a general-purpose VM</b>: stores keys in software on shared hardware, which does not provide the tamper-resistant hardware boundary the requirement demands.</span><span class='qd'><b>Certificate signing request</b>: is a message requesting a certificate from a CA; it is not a key-protection mechanism at all.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reverse proxy</b>: terminates or forwards connections and can offload TLS, but it is not a hardware key-protection boundary.</span>"},{"id":"D1-016","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"medium","q":"During design, a CCSP maps a data element through create, store, use, share, archive, and destroy. Which framework is being applied, and why does it matter for cloud design?","options":["The OSI model, to segment network layers","The STRIDE model, to enumerate application threats","The Deming cycle, to drive continual improvement","The cloud secure data lifecycle, to apply appropriate controls at each phase"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The cloud secure data lifecycle, to apply appropriate controls at each phase</strong> — the six phases (create, store, use, share, archive, destroy) let designers attach the right protections (classification, encryption, access, retention, sanitization) at every stage.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The OSI model, to segment network layers</b>: describes networking layers, not the phases a data element passes through.</span><span class='qd'><b>The STRIDE model, to enumerate application threats</b>: is a threat-modeling taxonomy (spoofing, tampering, etc.), not a data lifecycle.</span><span class='qd'><b>The Deming cycle, to drive continual improvement</b>: is the plan-do-check-act management loop, unrelated to tracking data through lifecycle phases.</span>"},{"id":"D1-017","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP is asked which capability type corresponds to the ability to deploy consumer-created or acquired applications using programming languages and tools supported by the provider. Which capability type is this?","options":["Platform capability","Infrastructure capability","Application capability","Governance capability"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Platform capability</strong> — the platform capability type, per the cloud reference architecture, is the ability to deploy consumer-created or acquired applications using languages and tools the provider supports (the essence of PaaS).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Infrastructure capability</b>: is the ability to provision processing, storage, and networks and run arbitrary software including OSes (IaaS), a lower layer than deploying apps on a supported platform.</span><span class='qd'><b>Application capability</b>: is the ability to use the provider's applications (SaaS), not to deploy one's own code.</span><span class='qd'><b>Governance capability</b>: is not one of the three capability types (application, platform, infrastructure) defined in the reference architecture.</span>"},{"id":"D1-018","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"hard","q":"A workload processes highly sensitive data and the organization is worried about the cloud provider's own administrators being able to read data while it is being processed in memory. Which emerging technology most directly addresses this specific concern?","options":["Data-at-rest encryption","Confidential computing with a trusted execution environment","TLS 1.3 for data in transit","Immutable object storage"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Confidential computing with a trusted execution environment</strong> — confidential computing protects data in use by processing it inside a hardware-based TEE (enclave) that shields it even from the host and provider administrators.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data-at-rest encryption</b>: protects stored data but leaves it exposed in plaintext in memory during processing, which is exactly the gap here.</span><span class='qd'><b>TLS 1.3 for data in transit</b>: secures data moving over the network, not data being computed on in memory.</span><span class='qd'><b>Immutable object storage</b>: prevents modification/deletion of stored objects (integrity/retention) and does nothing for confidentiality of data in use.</span>"},{"id":"D1-019","domain":1,"obj":"1.1","diff":"easy","q":"A developer provisions a new database instance instantly through a self-service web portal, with no ticket to IT and no human approval in the loop. Which essential characteristic is demonstrated?","options":["Resource pooling","Rapid elasticity","On-demand self-service","Measured service"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>On-demand self-service</strong> — provisioning computing capabilities automatically, without requiring human interaction with the provider, is the definition of on-demand self-service.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Resource pooling</b>: refers to multi-tenant sharing of provider resources, not to self-service provisioning.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rapid elasticity</b>: is about scaling capacity up and down; a single instance being provisioned is provisioning, not elastic scaling.</span><span class='qd'><b>Measured service</b>: concerns metering and billing, which the scenario does not emphasize.</span>"},{"id":"D1-020","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"medium","q":"An enterprise deliberately spreads workloads across three different public cloud providers to avoid dependence on any single one and to negotiate better terms. Which deployment strategy is this, and what is a primary trade-off?","options":["Hybrid cloud; simpler unified management","Private cloud; loss of elasticity","Community cloud; shared compliance burden","Multi-cloud; increased operational and integration complexity"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Multi-cloud; increased operational and integration complexity</strong> — using multiple public providers is multi-cloud, and its main trade-off is added complexity in management, integration, skills, and consistent security across heterogeneous platforms.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Hybrid cloud; simpler unified management</b>: mislabels the strategy (hybrid mixes deployment models, not several public providers) and wrongly claims simplification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Private cloud; loss of elasticity</b>: is incorrect because the scenario uses public providers, not a single-tenant private cloud.</span><span class='qd'><b>Community cloud; shared compliance burden</b>: applies to multiple organizations with common concerns sharing one environment, not one enterprise spreading across vendors.</span>"},{"id":"D1-021","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud team wants to restrict inbound and outbound traffic to a group of VMs based on port, protocol, and source, applied at the virtual instance level rather than a subnet boundary. Which control fits best?","options":["Security group","DNSSEC","Geofencing","Data loss prevention"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Security group</strong> — a security group is a virtual, instance-level stateful firewall that filters traffic by port, protocol, and source/destination, which matches the requirement exactly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>DNSSEC</b>: adds authentication of DNS responses to prevent spoofing; it does not filter instance traffic.</span><span class='qd'><b>Geofencing</b>: restricts access by geographic location, a coarser control than per-instance port/protocol filtering.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data loss prevention</b>: inspects and blocks sensitive data movement; it is a content-based control, not a network port/protocol firewall at the instance level.</span>"},{"id":"D1-022","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"hard","q":"A CCSP is documenting who is responsible for which controls under SaaS, PaaS, and IaaS. Which statement correctly captures how responsibility shifts across these models?","options":["The customer's responsibility is greatest in SaaS and least in IaaS","The provider's responsibility is greatest in SaaS and least in IaaS","Responsibility is identical across all three models","In all models the customer is solely responsible for physical security"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The provider's responsibility is greatest in SaaS and least in IaaS</strong> — moving from IaaS to PaaS to SaaS, the provider assumes progressively more of the stack, so provider responsibility is highest in SaaS and lowest in IaaS (and customer responsibility is the inverse).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The customer's responsibility is greatest in SaaS and least in IaaS</b>: reverses the truth; the customer manages the most in IaaS, not SaaS.</span><span class='qd'><b>Responsibility is identical across all three models</b>: contradicts the defining principle that responsibility shifts with the service model.</span><span class='qd'><b>In all models the customer is solely responsible for physical security</b>: is false; the provider always owns physical/data-center security in these models.</span>"},{"id":"D1-023","domain":1,"obj":"1.1","diff":"easy","q":"In cloud computing, when a single physical or logical resource simultaneously serves multiple independent customers whose data must remain logically isolated, this property is called:","options":["Redundancy","Federation","Multi-tenancy","Elasticity"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Multi-tenancy</strong> — multi-tenancy is the property of a single resource serving multiple distinct tenants with logical isolation between their data and configurations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Redundancy</b>: duplicates components for availability; it is not about serving multiple customers on one resource.</span><span class='qd'><b>Federation</b>: links identity across separate trust domains, not shared tenancy of a resource.</span><span class='qd'><b>Elasticity</b>: is the ability to scale capacity, unrelated to multiple tenants sharing a resource.</span>"},{"id":"D1-024","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"An organization wants ephemeral compute that runs code only in response to events, scales to zero when idle, and requires no server management. Which virtualization/compute model is described, and what is a key security consideration?","options":["Type 1 hypervisor; firmware attestation","Container registry; image signing only","Bare-metal server; BIOS hardening","Serverless (FaaS); minimizing function permissions and managing dependencies"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Serverless (FaaS); minimizing function permissions and managing dependencies</strong> — event-driven code that scales to zero with no server management is serverless/FaaS, and key concerns are least-privilege function roles, secure dependencies, and short-lived execution context.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Type 1 hypervisor; firmware attestation</b>: describes a bare-metal hypervisor, not the event-driven, scale-to-zero code model in the scenario.</span><span class='qd'><b>Container registry; image signing only</b>: a registry stores images and does not itself provide event-driven ephemeral execution.</span><span class='qd'><b>Bare-metal server; BIOS hardening</b>: is dedicated physical hardware, the opposite of the abstract, no-server-management model described.</span>"},{"id":"D1-025","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"hard","q":"A regulator asks how the organization ensures that if it later migrates away, its data and application logic can move to a different provider with minimal rework. Two shared considerations are most relevant. Which pair is it?","options":["Portability and interoperability","Availability and performance","Privacy and auditability","Resiliency and governance"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Portability and interoperability</strong> — portability lets data and workloads move between environments, and interoperability lets systems work together across providers; together they minimize rework and lock-in on migration.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability and performance</b>: concern uptime and responsiveness, not the ability to migrate between providers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Privacy and auditability</b>: address data protection and verifiability of records, not workload mobility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Resiliency and governance</b>: address fault tolerance and oversight, which do not directly enable moving to another provider.</span>"},{"id":"D1-026","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"A security team standardizes a hardened, minimal configuration image that all new servers must be built from, then continuously measures deployed systems against it. Which two hygiene practices are being applied?","options":["Tokenization and masking","Baselining and configuration management","Federation and single sign-on","Sharding and replication"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Baselining and configuration management</strong> — defining a secure standard build (baseline) and continuously verifying systems against it is baselining supported by configuration management, a core security-hygiene practice.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Tokenization and masking</b>: are data-obfuscation techniques for protecting sensitive values, not system configuration control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Federation and single sign-on</b>: are identity concepts for cross-domain authentication, unrelated to hardened build standards.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sharding and replication</b>: are data-distribution and availability techniques, not configuration baselining.</span>"},{"id":"D1-027","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"hard","q":"A CCSP is performing a business impact analysis for a proposed cloud migration and must justify it financially to leadership. Which pairing best reflects the BIA's economic focus?","options":["Threat modeling and abuse cases","Penetration testing and red teaming","Cost-benefit analysis and return on investment","Data classification and labeling"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Cost-benefit analysis and return on investment</strong> — the economic dimension of a BIA for a migration decision weighs costs against benefits and expected ROI to justify the investment to leadership.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Threat modeling and abuse cases</b>: are application-security design activities, not the financial justification a BIA provides.</span><span class='qd'><b>Penetration testing and red teaming</b>: are offensive security assessments, unrelated to a cost-based migration justification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data classification and labeling</b>: are data-governance activities and do not constitute the economic analysis requested.</span>"},{"id":"D1-028","domain":1,"obj":"1.1","diff":"easy","q":"Which NIST role represents the entity that maintains a business relationship with, and uses services from, a cloud provider?","options":["Cloud provider","Cloud carrier","Cloud auditor","Cloud consumer (customer)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Cloud consumer (customer)</strong> — the cloud consumer is the person or organization that maintains a business relationship with, and uses service from, a cloud provider.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud provider</b>: is the entity responsible for making the service available, the counterparty to the consumer.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud carrier</b>: provides connectivity and transport of services, not the consuming party.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud auditor</b>: independently examines controls and performance; it does not consume the service for business use.</span>"},{"id":"D1-029","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"An architect wants to inspect east-west traffic between microservices for malicious payloads without terminating each service's TLS at the application. Which network-security capability is most appropriate?","options":["Traffic inspection at a service mesh or inspection point","Geofencing by client country","Cryptographic erasure","Measured service metering"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Traffic inspection at a service mesh or inspection point</strong> — inspecting east-west traffic for malicious content is a traffic-inspection control, commonly implemented via a service mesh sidecar or dedicated inspection point that can observe decrypted flows.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Geofencing by client country</b>: filters based on geographic origin of clients, not deep inspection of inter-service payloads.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cryptographic erasure</b>: is a data-destruction technique, unrelated to inspecting live traffic.</span><span class='qd'><b>Measured service metering</b>: is a billing characteristic, not a security inspection capability.</span>"},{"id":"D1-030","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP notes that a proposed blockchain-based supply-chain ledger will store data immutably across many nodes. Which security property is a primary strength, and which is a primary challenge, of this design?","options":["Strength: confidentiality of on-chain data; challenge: availability","Strength: integrity and non-repudiation; challenge: privacy/right-to-erasure of on-chain data","Strength: elasticity; challenge: metering","Strength: portability; challenge: interoperability"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Strength: integrity and non-repudiation; challenge: privacy/right-to-erasure of on-chain data</strong> — blockchain's append-only, cryptographically linked ledger gives strong integrity and non-repudiation, but immutability conflicts with privacy regimes' right-to-erasure and can expose data across nodes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Strength: confidentiality of on-chain data; challenge: availability</b>: is backwards; public ledgers are typically transparent, so confidentiality is a weakness and availability a strength of distributed nodes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Strength: elasticity; challenge: metering</b>: names generic cloud characteristics that are not the defining security properties of blockchain.</span><span class='qd'><b>Strength: portability; challenge: interoperability</b>: are migration considerations, not the integrity-versus-privacy tension central to blockchain.</span>"},{"id":"D1-031","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"hard","q":"A CCSP must choose a media-sanitization method for solid-state drives (SSDs) that were used for confidential data before redeployment. Why is a traditional multi-pass overwrite considered unreliable for SSDs?","options":["SSDs are too slow to overwrite fully","Overwriting corrupts the file system permanently","Wear-leveling and over-provisioning can leave data in cells the overwrite command cannot address","SSDs cannot store confidential data"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Wear-leveling and over-provisioning can leave data in cells the overwrite command cannot address</strong> — SSD controllers remap writes across cells (wear-leveling) and reserve spare capacity (over-provisioning), so a logical overwrite may never touch physical cells still holding old data; crypto-erase or vendor secure-erase is preferred.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SSDs are too slow to overwrite fully</b>: is false; SSDs are fast, and speed is not the reliability issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>Overwriting corrupts the file system permanently</b>: is not the reason; the concern is residual data, not file-system damage.</span><span class='qd'><b>SSDs cannot store confidential data</b>: is simply untrue and irrelevant to sanitization reliability.</span>"},{"id":"D1-032","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP is asked which service category places the greatest secure-configuration burden on the customer for the guest operating system, network controls, and application stack.","options":["SaaS","PaaS","FaaS","IaaS"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>IaaS</strong> — in IaaS the provider supplies raw compute, storage, and networking, leaving the customer responsible for the guest OS, network controls, middleware, and applications, the largest configuration burden of the service categories.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SaaS</b>: places the least burden on the customer, who mostly configures application settings and access, not the OS.</span><span class='qd'><b>PaaS</b>: hands OS and runtime management to the provider, so the customer's OS burden is far smaller than in IaaS.</span><span class='qd'><b>FaaS</b>: abstracts servers entirely; the customer manages only function code and permissions, not the guest OS.</span>"},{"id":"D1-033","domain":1,"obj":"1.1","diff":"medium","q":"A provider abstracts storage, compute, and networking into pools and dynamically assigns and reassigns resources according to demand, with the customer generally unaware of the exact physical location of the resources. Which characteristic does the location-independence aspect describe?","options":["Resource pooling","Broad network access","On-demand self-service","Rapid elasticity"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Resource pooling</strong> — resource pooling includes location independence: resources are pooled and dynamically assigned, and the customer generally has no control or knowledge of the exact physical location.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Broad network access</b>: is about reachability from varied client devices over the network, not physical-location abstraction of pooled resources.</span><span class='qd'><b>On-demand self-service</b>: is about provisioning without human interaction, not location abstraction.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rapid elasticity</b>: is about scaling capacity, not the pooling and location-independence described.</span>"},{"id":"D1-034","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"hard","q":"A CCSP is advising on functional security requirements to reduce the risk of vendor lock-in for a mission-critical SaaS. Which design measure most directly mitigates lock-in?","options":["Choosing the provider with the lowest price","Requiring open standards, documented data-export formats, and a contractual exit/reversibility clause","Encrypting all data at rest with provider-managed keys","Enabling autoscaling for peak demand"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Requiring open standards, documented data-export formats, and a contractual exit/reversibility clause</strong> — lock-in is mitigated by favoring open standards and portable formats and by contractually guaranteeing data export and a clean exit (reversibility), preserving the ability to switch providers.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Choosing the provider with the lowest price</b>: addresses cost, not the technical and contractual barriers that create lock-in.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypting all data at rest with provider-managed keys</b>: can actually worsen lock-in if the provider controls the keys, and does not enable portability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Enabling autoscaling for peak demand</b>: is a performance/elasticity feature unrelated to the ability to leave a provider.</span>"},{"id":"D1-035","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP reviews a design that grants every developer standing administrative access to the production management plane 'for convenience.' Which principle is violated and what is the best remediation?","options":["Separation of duties; merge all roles into one","Defense in depth; remove all monitoring","Least privilege; grant just-in-time, scoped privileged access instead","Non-repudiation; disable logging"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Least privilege; grant just-in-time, scoped privileged access instead</strong> — standing admin access to the management plane violates least privilege; the fix is time-bound, narrowly scoped just-in-time elevation with approval and logging.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Separation of duties; merge all roles into one</b>: names a relevant principle but proposes the opposite remediation; merging roles concentrates privilege further.</span><span class='qd'><b>Defense in depth; remove all monitoring</b>: is nonsensical as a remediation because removing monitoring reduces, not improves, security.</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-repudiation; disable logging</b>: contradicts itself, since disabling logging destroys the ability to attribute actions.</span>"},{"id":"D1-036","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"easy","q":"A company uses a provider's fully managed email and productivity suite accessed through a browser, configuring only tenant policies and user accounts. Which service category is this?","options":["IaaS","PaaS","Bare metal","SaaS"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>SaaS</strong> — using a complete, provider-managed application over the browser while configuring only settings and users is Software as a Service.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>IaaS</b>: would require the customer to run its own OS and application on provisioned infrastructure, which is not the case here.</span><span class='qd'><b>PaaS</b>: provides a platform for the customer to deploy its own applications; the customer here deploys nothing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Bare metal</b>: is dedicated physical hardware the customer fully manages, the opposite of a browser-accessed managed suite.</span>"},{"id":"D1-037","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"hard","q":"A CCSP is asked to compare the isolation strength of containers versus virtual machines for running two mutually distrusting tenants on shared hosts. Which statement is most accurate?","options":["VMs generally provide stronger isolation because each has its own kernel, while containers share the host kernel","Containers provide stronger isolation because they include a full guest OS","Containers and VMs provide identical isolation guarantees","Neither provides any tenant isolation"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>VMs generally provide stronger isolation because each has its own kernel, while containers share the host kernel</strong> — VMs run separate guest kernels on top of a hypervisor, giving a stronger isolation boundary; containers share the host kernel, so a kernel compromise can affect all containers, making them weaker for mutually distrusting tenants.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Containers provide stronger isolation because they include a full guest OS</b>: is factually wrong; containers do not include a full guest OS and share the host kernel.</span><span class='qd'><b>Containers and VMs provide identical isolation guarantees</b>: ignores the fundamental difference in kernel separation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Neither provides any tenant isolation</b>: is false; both provide isolation, just at different strengths.</span>"},{"id":"D1-038","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"medium","q":"When designing a cloud-based BC/DR plan, a CCSP wants to exploit a native cloud advantage over traditional recovery sites. Which capability most directly reduces recovery time and standing cost?","options":["Physically shipping backup tapes to a warm site","On-demand, rapidly elastic provisioning of recovery capacity in another region","Maintaining a fully staffed duplicate data center","Disabling replication to save bandwidth"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>On-demand, rapidly elastic provisioning of recovery capacity in another region</strong> — cloud lets you spin up recovery capacity on demand in another region only when needed, lowering standing cost and speeding recovery compared with maintaining idle physical infrastructure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Physically shipping backup tapes to a warm site</b>: is a slow, traditional approach that increases recovery time, not a cloud advantage.</span><span class='qd'><b>Maintaining a fully staffed duplicate data center</b>: is exactly the high standing cost cloud DR aims to avoid.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling replication to save bandwidth</b>: would harm recoverability by widening the recovery point, contradicting DR goals.</span>"},{"id":"D1-039","domain":1,"obj":"1.1","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP explains that a database-as-a-service offering, an object storage service, and a virtual network are all examples of what in cloud terms?","options":["Deployment models","Cloud roles","Cloud building blocks (compute, storage, networking, database services)","Trust boundaries"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Cloud building blocks (compute, storage, networking, database services)</strong> — databases, object storage, and virtual networks are foundational cloud building blocks (compute, storage, networking, database, orchestration) that combine to form solutions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Deployment models</b>: are public, private, hybrid, community, and multi-cloud, not individual services like storage or databases.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud roles</b>: are actors such as consumer, provider, and broker, not technical service components.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trust boundaries</b>: are logical lines where trust levels change; they are an analysis concept, not a category for these services.</span>"},{"id":"D1-040","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP must advise on the security implication of adopting many Internet of Things (IoT) sensors feeding a cloud analytics platform. Which concern is most characteristic of IoT in this architecture?","options":["Excessive CPU in the cloud tier","Inability to meter usage","Lack of broad network access","A large, hard-to-patch device attack surface with weak device-level security"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A large, hard-to-patch device attack surface with weak device-level security</strong> — IoT deployments introduce many constrained, often poorly secured and hard-to-update endpoints, dramatically expanding the attack surface feeding the cloud platform.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Excessive CPU in the cloud tier</b>: is a capacity/performance matter, not the defining security concern of IoT.</span><span class='qd'><b>Inability to meter usage</b>: is unrelated; metering is a provider capability independent of IoT.</span><span class='qd'><b>Lack of broad network access</b>: is incorrect since IoT devices are network-connected by design; connectivity is a source of exposure, not a lack.</span>"},{"id":"D1-041","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"hard","q":"A key-management design must let the customer retain sole control over encryption keys used by a SaaS provider, so that even the provider cannot decrypt customer data without customer authorization. Which approach best achieves this?","options":["Customer-managed keys where the customer holds the key material, often via BYOK/HYOK with an external HSM","Provider-managed keys stored in the provider's default KMS","Hashing the data with SHA-256","Disabling encryption to simplify audits"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Customer-managed keys where the customer holds the key material, often via BYOK/HYOK with an external HSM</strong> — customer-held keys (bring/hold your own key), especially anchored in a customer-controlled HSM, ensure the provider cannot decrypt data without the customer authorizing key use.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Provider-managed keys stored in the provider's default KMS</b>: leaves key control with the provider, so it can technically decrypt the data, defeating the requirement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hashing the data with SHA-256</b>: is a one-way integrity function; it does not provide reversible encryption or customer key control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling encryption to simplify audits</b>: removes confidentiality protection entirely, the opposite of the goal.</span>"},{"id":"D1-042","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"easy","q":"A CCSP describes an activity where the provider is responsible for making service available and the customer is responsible for using it appropriately. In the cloud reference architecture, these divisions of duty are called:","options":["Encryption schemes","Cloud activities and responsibilities","Threat models","Storage tiers"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Cloud activities and responsibilities</strong> — the reference architecture defines cloud activities and the responsibilities each role carries out, describing who does what across provider and customer.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encryption schemes</b>: are cryptographic methods, not a description of role activities and responsibilities.</span><span class='qd'><b>Threat models</b>: enumerate potential attacks, unrelated to defining provider/customer duties.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storage tiers</b>: classify data storage by cost/performance, not the division of responsibilities.</span>"},{"id":"D1-043","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"After a workload is destroyed, a CCSP is concerned that fragments of sensitive data may persist in previously allocated cloud storage or memory. What is this residual-data risk called, and what is the best cloud-native mitigation?","options":["Data sovereignty; store data in-region","Data dispersion; use a single availability zone","Data remanence; encrypt data and crypto-shred the keys","Data classification; label everything as public"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Data remanence; encrypt data and crypto-shred the keys</strong> — residual data left after deletion is data remanence; in the cloud the reliable mitigation is to encrypt from the start and destroy the keys (crypto-shredding), rendering any remnants unreadable.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data sovereignty; store data in-region</b>: addresses legal jurisdiction over data location, not leftover data fragments.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data dispersion; use a single availability zone</b>: mislabels the risk and gives an availability-reducing action irrelevant to remanence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data classification; label everything as public</b>: is a labeling activity, not a remediation for residual sensitive data.</span>"},{"id":"D1-044","domain":1,"obj":"1.1","diff":"easy","q":"Which entity, in the NIST reference model, provides the network connectivity and transport of cloud services between the cloud consumer and cloud provider?","options":["Cloud broker","Cloud auditor","Cloud regulator","Cloud carrier"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Cloud carrier</strong> — the cloud carrier is the intermediary that provides connectivity and transport of cloud services from providers to consumers, typically via network and telecommunication access.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud broker</b>: manages use, performance, and delivery and negotiates relationships; it does not primarily provide network transport.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud auditor</b>: independently assesses controls and performance, not connectivity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud regulator</b>: is an oversight/legal authority, not a provider of network transport.</span>"},{"id":"D1-045","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"hard","q":"A CCSP is concerned that credentials embedded in application code and pipeline scripts are being leaked. Which security concept and control best addresses secure handling of these values across the environment?","options":["Centralized secrets management with dynamic, short-lived credentials","Geofencing enforced at the load balancer","Full-disk encryption on developer laptops","Network address translation at the edge"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Centralized secrets management with dynamic, short-lived credentials</strong> — a secrets-management service stores and injects credentials centrally and can issue dynamic, short-lived secrets, removing hard-coded values and limiting the blast radius of any leak.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Geofencing enforced at the load balancer</b>: restricts access by location and does nothing about credentials embedded in code.</span><span class='qd'><b>Full-disk encryption on developer laptops</b>: protects data at rest on the device but not secrets committed into shared code or pipelines.</span><span class='qd'><b>Network address translation at the edge</b>: rewrites addresses and has no bearing on secret storage or rotation.</span>"},{"id":"D1-046","domain":1,"obj":"1.2","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP is evaluating how confidential computing changes the shared-responsibility picture. Which statement best captures its design value in a public cloud?","options":["It removes the need for encryption at rest and in transit","It protects data in use so that even a compromised host or provider operator cannot read it in the enclave","It guarantees data portability between providers","It eliminates the need for identity and access management"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It protects data in use so that even a compromised host or provider operator cannot read it in the enclave</strong> — confidential computing closes the 'data in use' gap by isolating computation in a hardware enclave, shielding it from the host OS, hypervisor, and provider operators.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It removes the need for encryption at rest and in transit</b>: is false; confidential computing complements, not replaces, at-rest and in-transit encryption.</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees data portability between providers</b>: confuses it with portability; enclaves protect data in use, not migration.</span><span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for identity and access management</b>: is wrong; IAM remains essential regardless of enclave protection.</span>"},{"id":"D1-047","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP is assigning security responsibilities per service category during design. For a PaaS solution, which responsibility clearly remains with the customer?","options":["Patching the underlying operating system","Securing the physical data center","Securing the application code and its data, and managing access to them","Maintaining the hypervisor"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Securing the application code and its data, and managing access to them</strong> — in PaaS the provider manages the platform and OS, while the customer remains responsible for the security of the code it deploys, its data, and access controls over both.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Patching the underlying operating system</b>: is the provider's job in PaaS, not the customer's.</span><span class='qd'><b>Securing the physical data center</b>: is always the provider's responsibility across IaaS/PaaS/SaaS.</span><span class='qd'><b>Maintaining the hypervisor</b>: sits below the platform layer and is managed by the provider in PaaS.</span>"},{"id":"D1-048","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP wants independent assurance that a cloud provider has implemented information-security controls specifically tailored to cloud services, aligned to an ISO standard. Which standard is most directly relevant?","options":["PCI DSS","FIPS 140-3","ISO/IEC 9001","ISO/IEC 27017"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>ISO/IEC 27017</strong> — ISO/IEC 27017 provides a code of practice for information-security controls specifically for cloud services, extending 27002 with cloud-specific guidance, making it the most directly relevant benchmark.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>PCI DSS</b>: governs protection of payment card data; it is relevant only where cardholder data is processed, not a general cloud-security control set.</span><span class='qd'><b>FIPS 140-3</b>: validates cryptographic modules, a narrower product-certification scope than provider-wide cloud controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 9001</b>: addresses quality-management systems, not information security.</span>"},{"id":"D1-049","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"hard","q":"A procurement team requires that a security product used in a regulated environment carry an internationally recognized product-security evaluation. Which certification is designed for evaluating the security assurance of IT products against defined criteria?","options":["Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408)","SOC 2 Type II","ISO/IEC 27018","GDPR certification"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408)</strong> — the Common Criteria is the international standard for evaluating the security assurance of IT products against protection profiles and evaluation assurance levels, the correct product-certification fit.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 2 Type II</b>: attests to an organization's controls over a period, not the security assurance of a specific product.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27018</b>: is a code of practice for protecting PII in public clouds, a privacy control set, not a product evaluation.</span><span class='qd'><b>GDPR certification</b>: relates to data-protection compliance, not technical product-security assurance evaluation.</span>"},{"id":"D1-050","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"hard","q":"A CCSP is designing for the risk that a future quantum computer could break today's public-key cryptography protecting long-lived archived data. Which design response best mitigates this 'harvest-now, decrypt-later' concern?","options":["Increase symmetric key rotation frequency only","Plan migration to quantum-safe (post-quantum) cryptographic algorithms and crypto-agility","Switch all data to hashing instead of encryption","Rely solely on network segmentation"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Plan migration to quantum-safe (post-quantum) cryptographic algorithms and crypto-agility</strong> — harvested ciphertext could be decrypted once quantum computers mature, so the mitigation is to adopt post-quantum algorithms and build crypto-agility so algorithms can be swapped as standards evolve.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increase symmetric key rotation frequency only</b>: does not address the exposure of already-harvested asymmetric-protected data and ignores the algorithm-vulnerability root cause.</span><span class='qd'><b>Switch all data to hashing instead of encryption</b>: is unworkable because hashing is one-way and cannot protect data that must be recovered.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely solely on network segmentation</b>: does nothing for data an adversary has already exfiltrated to decrypt later.</span>"},{"id":"D1-051","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"easy","q":"An architect maps a control set to the six phases of the cloud secure data lifecycle. In which phase is data first assigned a classification and encryption applied so protections travel with it thereafter?","options":["Store","Use","Create","Archive"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Create</strong> — classification, labeling, and initial encryption are best applied at the moment data is generated so every downstream phase inherits the correct protections.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Store</b>: by the time data is at rest it should already carry its classification; retrofitting it here misses data that was used or shared first.</span><span class='qd'><b>Use</b>: data in use is decrypted and processed; classifying only now leaves a window where unlabeled data existed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Archive</b>: archiving is late in the lifecycle and is about long-term retention, not first classification.</span>"},{"id":"D1-052","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"A security team wants to guarantee that decommissioned SaaS-tenant data on shared multi-tenant storage is rendered unrecoverable without physically destroying disks they do not own. Which technique best fits this cloud constraint?","options":["Degaussing the storage array","A single-pass zero overwrite of the logical volume","Physical shredding of the drives","Cryptographic erasure (crypto-shredding) by destroying the keys"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Cryptographic erasure (crypto-shredding) by destroying the keys</strong> — in multi-tenant cloud storage the customer cannot access physical media, so destroying the encryption keys makes the ciphertext unrecoverable regardless of who else shares the hardware.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Degaussing the storage array</b>: the customer has no physical access and degaussing would destroy other tenants' data on shared media.</span><span class='qd'><b>A single-pass zero overwrite of the logical volume</b>: cloud abstraction and data dispersion mean an overwrite may not reach every physical copy or replica.</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical shredding of the drives</b>: impossible for a tenant on provider-owned shared hardware.</span>"},{"id":"D1-053","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"easy","q":"During CSP selection, a bank requires assurance that a submitted hardware security module meets a recognized cryptographic-module standard. Which certification should the CSP present?","options":["FIPS 140-2/140-3","SOC 2 Type II","ISO/IEC 27001","PCI DSS AoC"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>FIPS 140-2/140-3</strong> — this is the standard specifically validating cryptographic modules such as HSMs, exactly the assurance the bank needs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 2 Type II</b>: attests to operating effectiveness of trust-service controls, not the cryptographic module itself.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27001</b>: certifies an information security management system, not a crypto module.</span><span class='qd'><b>PCI DSS AoC</b>: attests cardholder-data environment compliance, not module-level cryptographic validation.</span>"},{"id":"D1-054","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"medium","q":"A procurement lead needs an internationally recognized code of practice specifically for information security controls in cloud services to benchmark candidate providers. Which standard is the most direct fit?","options":["ISO/IEC 27002","ISO/IEC 27017","ISO/IEC 27018","ISO/IEC 27701"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>ISO/IEC 27017</strong> — it is the cloud-specific code of practice for information security controls, tailored to CSP and customer responsibilities.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27002</b>: a general controls code of practice, not cloud-specific.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27018</b>: focuses on protecting PII in public clouds (privacy), not general cloud security controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27701</b>: extends 27001/27002 for privacy information management, not cloud security controls broadly.</span>"},{"id":"D1-055","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"hard","q":"An enterprise wants the freedom to move a workload between two providers with minimal re-engineering, and to retrieve all data and cleanly exit either provider. Which pair of functional requirements is the architect primarily addressing?","options":["Interoperability and elasticity","Resiliency and availability","Portability and reversibility","Multi-tenancy and measured service"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Portability and reversibility</strong> — portability enables moving workloads/data between providers, and reversibility enables a clean exit with full data retrieval and provider-side deletion.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Interoperability and elasticity</b>: interoperability is about systems working together, and elasticity is capacity scaling — neither is the move/exit concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Resiliency and availability</b>: these address uptime and fault tolerance, not migration or exit.</span><span class='qd'><b>Multi-tenancy and measured service</b>: these are essential cloud characteristics, not exit/migration requirements.</span>"},{"id":"D1-056","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"To reduce lateral movement inside a cloud VPC, an architect wants stateful, instance-level filtering that permits only required ports between application tiers. Which control most directly meets this need?","options":["A geofencing policy","A DNSSEC configuration","A web application firewall","A network security group (security group)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A network security group (security group)</strong> — security groups apply stateful allow-list filtering at the instance/interface level, ideal for restricting east-west traffic between tiers.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A geofencing policy</b>: restricts access by geographic location, not port-level tier segmentation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A DNSSEC configuration</b>: authenticates DNS responses; it does not filter traffic between tiers.</span><span class='qd'><b>A web application firewall</b>: inspects HTTP/S at layer 7 for a web app, not general east-west port filtering.</span>"},{"id":"D1-057","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"hard","q":"An architect is designing access for automated pipelines that call cloud APIs without a human present. Which identity approach best satisfies least privilege while avoiding long-lived embedded secrets?","options":["A service identity with short-lived, scoped tokens","Shared root account credentials stored in the pipeline","A privileged human admin account reused by the pipeline","A single API key with full-account permissions"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A service identity with short-lived, scoped tokens</strong> — non-human workloads should use dedicated service identities issued narrowly scoped, time-bound credentials, minimizing blast radius and eliminating static secrets.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Shared root account credentials stored in the pipeline</b>: root is unrestricted and sharing it violates least privilege and non-repudiation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A privileged human admin account reused by the pipeline</b>: conflates human and machine identity and grants excess privilege.</span><span class='qd'><b>A single API key with full-account permissions</b>: a long-lived, over-scoped static secret is the exact anti-pattern to avoid.</span>"},{"id":"D1-058","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"medium","q":"A CISO argues that migrating a monolithic app to a single proprietary PaaS with unique managed services will be cheap now but risky later. Which secure-design concern is she raising?","options":["Broad network access","Vendor lock-in","Resource pooling","Measured service"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Vendor lock-in</strong> — heavy dependence on one provider's proprietary services makes future migration costly and difficult, a core functional-security/portability concern.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Broad network access</b>: an essential cloud characteristic about reachability, not dependency risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Resource pooling</b>: describes shared multi-tenant resources, unrelated to migration risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Measured service</b>: refers to metered, pay-per-use billing, not lock-in.</span>"},{"id":"D1-059","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"medium","q":"When building a cloud BC/DR plan, which activity should precede selecting recovery strategies because it quantifies impact and drives RTO/RPO targets?","options":["Tabletop exercise","Failover testing","Business impact analysis (BIA)","Runbook automation"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Business impact analysis (BIA)</strong> — the BIA quantifies the consequences of disruption and establishes the RTO/RPO that then justify the chosen recovery strategy and spend.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Tabletop exercise</b>: validates a plan after it exists; it does not set the impact-driven targets.</span><span class='qd'><b>Failover testing</b>: tests recovery mechanics later, once strategy and targets are chosen.</span><span class='qd'><b>Runbook automation</b>: implements recovery steps; it depends on strategy already selected.</span>"},{"id":"D1-060","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"hard","q":"A defense contractor needs independent assurance that a product's security functionality was evaluated against a defined protection profile at a stated assurance level. Which scheme should they require of the product?","options":["SOC 3 report","CSA STAR self-assessment","FedRAMP ATO letter","Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408) EAL"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408) EAL</strong> — Common Criteria evaluates a product against a protection profile and assigns an Evaluation Assurance Level, exactly matching the requirement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 3 report</b>: a general-use attestation about service controls, not a product evaluation with assurance levels.</span><span class='qd'><b>CSA STAR self-assessment</b>: a provider self-attestation of cloud controls, not an independent product evaluation.</span><span class='qd'><b>FedRAMP ATO letter</b>: authorizes a cloud service for U.S. federal use, not a product protection-profile evaluation.</span>"},{"id":"D1-061","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"easy","q":"An architect adopts a model where no user, device, or workload is trusted by default and every request is authenticated and authorized based on context. Which concept is this?","options":["Zero trust","Perimeter security","Implicit trust zones","Flat network design"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Zero trust</strong> — zero trust removes implicit trust and continuously verifies every request using identity and context regardless of network location.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Perimeter security</b>: relies on a trusted internal network behind a boundary, the opposite of zero trust.</span><span class='qd'><b>Implicit trust zones</b>: this is precisely what zero trust eliminates.</span><span class='qd'><b>Flat network design</b>: a topology with no segmentation, unrelated to per-request verification.</span>"},{"id":"D1-062","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"medium","q":"In an IaaS deployment, which security responsibility remains with the cloud customer rather than the provider?","options":["Physical data center access controls","Guest OS patching and hardening","Hypervisor maintenance","Underlying network fabric security"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Guest OS patching and hardening</strong> — in IaaS the customer manages everything from the operating system upward, including OS patching, hardening, and configuration.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical data center access controls</b>: always the provider's responsibility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hypervisor maintenance</b>: the provider owns and secures the virtualization layer.</span><span class='qd'><b>Underlying network fabric security</b>: the provider secures the physical/virtual fabric it operates.</span>"},{"id":"D1-063","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"hard","q":"A healthcare provider must process sensitive records in the cloud while keeping data protected even during computation, so the CSP administrators cannot read plaintext in memory. Which emerging technology best addresses this?","options":["Content delivery networks","Serverless functions","Confidential computing (trusted execution environments)","Immutable infrastructure"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Confidential computing (trusted execution environments)</strong> — TEEs encrypt and isolate data while it is in use, protecting plaintext in memory from the host and provider administrators.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Content delivery networks</b>: cache and distribute content for performance; they do not protect data in use.</span><span class='qd'><b>Serverless functions</b>: an execution model; by itself it does not shield memory from the host.</span><span class='qd'><b>Immutable infrastructure</b>: prevents drift by replacing rather than patching; unrelated to in-use memory confidentiality.</span>"},{"id":"D1-064","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"A team wants to ensure that ephemeral container workloads cannot retain sensitive data after they terminate. Which property of the design most directly provides this assurance?","options":["Long-lived attached volumes","Shared writable host directories","Persistent in-container databases","Statelessness with no persistent local storage"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Statelessness with no persistent local storage</strong> — stateless ephemeral containers hold no durable local data, so nothing sensitive survives termination.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Long-lived attached volumes</b>: persist data beyond the container's life, defeating the goal.</span><span class='qd'><b>Shared writable host directories</b>: leave data on the host after the container exits.</span><span class='qd'><b>Persistent in-container databases</b>: intentionally retain state, contradicting ephemerality.</span>"},{"id":"D1-065","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"medium","q":"A retailer that stores cardholder data on a CSP wants evidence the provider's in-scope environment meets card-industry requirements. Which artifact best supports vendor verification?","options":["The provider's PCI DSS Attestation of Compliance for its in-scope services","The provider's marketing whitepaper","A signed NDA","A generic ISO 9001 certificate"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The provider's PCI DSS Attestation of Compliance for its in-scope services</strong> — the PCI DSS AoC is the recognized evidence that the provider's relevant services meet cardholder-data requirements.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The provider's marketing whitepaper</b>: unverified vendor claims, not independent attestation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A signed NDA</b>: governs confidentiality of shared information, not compliance evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>A generic ISO 9001 certificate</b>: addresses quality management, not payment-card security.</span>"},{"id":"D1-066","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"hard","q":"Anticipating that today's public-key algorithms may be broken by future quantum computers, an architect wants to protect long-lived archived data from a harvest-now-decrypt-later threat. Which action is most appropriate now?","options":["Disable all encryption to simplify future migration","Adopt a crypto-agile design and plan migration to quantum-safe algorithms","Rely solely on longer RSA-2048 key lifetimes","Move the data to a private cloud and take no crypto action"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Adopt a crypto-agile design and plan migration to quantum-safe algorithms</strong> — crypto-agility lets the organization swap in post-quantum algorithms, and planning migration protects long-lived secrets from future decryption.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Disable all encryption to simplify future migration</b>: removes protection entirely, exposing data now.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely solely on longer RSA-2048 key lifetimes</b>: RSA is quantum-vulnerable; longer lifetimes do not help.</span><span class='qd'><b>Move the data to a private cloud and take no crypto action</b>: location does not address the cryptographic weakness.</span>"},{"id":"D1-067","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"easy","q":"To detect malicious payloads and policy violations in traffic flowing to a cloud application, which capability should the architect deploy?","options":["A measured-service meter","An elasticity autoscaler","Traffic inspection (IDS/IPS or deep packet inspection)","A resource-pooling scheduler"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Traffic inspection (IDS/IPS or deep packet inspection)</strong> — inspecting traffic content lets the system detect and block malicious payloads and policy violations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A measured-service meter</b>: tracks usage for billing, not threats.</span><span class='qd'><b>An elasticity autoscaler</b>: adjusts capacity to load, not a security inspection function.</span><span class='qd'><b>A resource-pooling scheduler</b>: allocates shared resources, unrelated to payload detection.</span>"},{"id":"D1-068","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"medium","q":"An organization moving to DevOps wants to embed security into the pipeline rather than bolting it on at the end. Which practice best reflects this secure-design intent?","options":["Manual security review only at go-live","A separate security team gate weeks after release","Ad hoc penetration testing once a year","Shift-left security integrated as DevSecOps"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Shift-left security integrated as DevSecOps</strong> — DevSecOps embeds automated security controls and testing early and throughout the pipeline, matching the intent.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Manual security review only at go-live</b>: bolts security on at the end, the anti-pattern being replaced.</span><span class='qd'><b>A separate security team gate weeks after release</b>: too late and outside the pipeline.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ad hoc penetration testing once a year</b>: infrequent and not integrated into development.</span>"},{"id":"D1-069","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"hard","q":"A financial firm performs a cost-benefit analysis for a cloud DR site. The annualized loss expectancy of an outage is far higher than the annual cost of a warm standby, but a hot site costs several times more for marginal RTO gains. Which decision best reflects sound BIA-driven design?","options":["Choose the warm standby, aligning spend to quantified risk and RTO","Always choose the hot site for maximum availability","Skip DR since cloud is inherently resilient","Choose the cheapest cold site regardless of RTO"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Choose the warm standby, aligning spend to quantified risk and RTO</strong> — a BIA/cost-benefit approach matches recovery investment to quantified impact and the required RTO, and the warm standby does that here.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Always choose the hot site for maximum availability</b>: overspends for marginal RTO gain the analysis does not justify.</span><span class='qd'><b>Skip DR since cloud is inherently resilient</b>: cloud is not automatically resilient to all failures; this ignores the ALE.</span><span class='qd'><b>Choose the cheapest cold site regardless of RTO</b>: ignores whether the RTO can be met, risking unacceptable downtime.</span>"},{"id":"D1-070","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"medium","q":"A customer wants a lightweight, publicly shareable summary attesting a CSP meets trust-services criteria without disclosing sensitive control detail. Which report fits?","options":["SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3","SOC 1 Type I","A full penetration-test report"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>SOC 3</strong> — SOC 3 is a general-use, publicly distributable summary of the same trust-services criteria as SOC 2, without the detailed control descriptions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 2 Type II</b>: detailed and restricted-use, not intended for public distribution.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 1 Type I</b>: addresses financial-reporting controls at a point in time, not trust-services criteria for public sharing.</span><span class='qd'><b>A full penetration-test report</b>: sensitive technical findings, the opposite of a shareable summary.</span>"},{"id":"D1-071","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"To restrict administrative console access to sessions originating only from the company's approved country, which control should the architect apply?","options":["Tokenization","Data masking","Geofencing","Load balancing"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Geofencing</strong> — geofencing enforces access decisions based on geographic origin, matching the country-restriction requirement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Tokenization</b>: substitutes sensitive values with tokens; it does not gate access by location.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data masking</b>: obscures data in displays; unrelated to session origin.</span><span class='qd'><b>Load balancing</b>: distributes traffic across resources, not a location-based access control.</span>"},{"id":"D1-072","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"hard","q":"A serverless function needs to read one secret at runtime. Which design best satisfies least privilege and secure secret handling?","options":["Hard-code the secret in the function source","Store the secret in an environment variable in plaintext and reuse it everywhere","Give the function full read access to the entire secrets store","Grant the function a scoped role to fetch the single secret from a managed vault at invocation"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Grant the function a scoped role to fetch the single secret from a managed vault at invocation</strong> — retrieving just the needed secret from a vault under a narrowly scoped role enforces least privilege and avoids embedded secrets.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Hard-code the secret in the function source</b>: exposes the secret in code and version control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Store the secret in an environment variable in plaintext and reuse it everywhere</b>: plaintext and broad reuse widen exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Give the function full read access to the entire secrets store</b>: violates least privilege by over-granting.</span>"},{"id":"D1-073","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"medium","q":"An architect wants two SaaS platforms from different vendors to exchange data using shared standards so neither has to build custom adapters. Which functional requirement is being pursued?","options":["Interoperability","Reversibility","Elasticity","Multi-tenancy"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Interoperability</strong> — interoperability is the ability of different systems to work together via common standards and interfaces, exactly what is described.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Reversibility</b>: concerns cleanly exiting a provider and retrieving data, not inter-system data exchange.</span><span class='qd'><b>Elasticity</b>: scaling capacity with demand, unrelated to standards-based exchange.</span><span class='qd'><b>Multi-tenancy</b>: sharing infrastructure among tenants, not data interchange between vendors.</span>"},{"id":"D1-074","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"easy","q":"A vendor claims strong controls but offers only a self-completed questionnaire. What is the primary weakness of relying on it alone during CSP evaluation?","options":["It is too detailed to review","It lacks independent third-party verification","It is legally binding on the customer","It automatically expires monthly"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It lacks independent third-party verification</strong> — a self-assessment reflects the vendor's own claims without an independent auditor validating them, limiting assurance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It is too detailed to review</b>: level of detail is not the core assurance problem.</span><span class='qd'><b>It is legally binding on the customer</b>: a questionnaire does not bind the customer.</span><span class='qd'><b>It automatically expires monthly</b>: expiry cadence is not the fundamental weakness.</span>"},{"id":"D1-075","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"An architect must ensure cryptographic keys used by a cloud service are generated, stored, and rotated so that even the provider cannot access customer plaintext keys. Which approach best supports this control objective?","options":["Provider-managed keys with no customer visibility","Embedding keys in application config files","Customer-managed keys backed by an HSM/KMS with controlled key custody","Sharing one static key across all tenants"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Customer-managed keys backed by an HSM/KMS with controlled key custody</strong> — customer control of key material in an HSM/KMS, with rotation and custody policies, keeps plaintext keys out of the provider's reach.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Provider-managed keys with no customer visibility</b>: leaves custody and access entirely with the provider.</span><span class='qd'><b>Embedding keys in application config files</b>: exposes keys in plaintext artifacts.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sharing one static key across all tenants</b>: breaks tenant isolation and rotation goals.</span>"},{"id":"D1-076","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"hard","q":"A firm negotiating a cloud contract wants to preserve its ability to exit and to obtain code/data if the provider fails. Which combination best supports reversibility and continuity?","options":["A perpetual auto-renew clause with no exit terms","Reliance on the provider's proprietary export tool only","A verbal assurance from the sales team","Documented data-export formats plus a software/source escrow arrangement"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Documented data-export formats plus a software/source escrow arrangement</strong> — portable export formats enable data retrieval and escrow provides access to code/assets if the provider fails, together supporting reversibility and continuity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A perpetual auto-renew clause with no exit terms</b>: worsens lock-in and blocks exit.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reliance on the provider's proprietary export tool only</b>: creates dependency and may not survive provider failure.</span><span class='qd'><b>A verbal assurance from the sales team</b>: unenforceable and provides no continuity mechanism.</span>"},{"id":"D1-077","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is a routine security-hygiene practice that reduces the attack surface of cloud virtual machines over time?","options":["Regular patching and baseline configuration","Disabling all logging","Granting all users administrator rights","Turning off encryption to save cost"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Regular patching and baseline configuration</strong> — keeping systems patched and configured to a hardened baseline reduces exploitable weaknesses.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling all logging</b>: removes visibility and hinders detection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Granting all users administrator rights</b>: violates least privilege and widens attack surface.</span><span class='qd'><b>Turning off encryption to save cost</b>: exposes data and weakens security.</span>"},{"id":"D1-078","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"medium","q":"In a SaaS model, which security responsibility is almost entirely retained by the customer despite the provider managing the application?","options":["Patching the application code","Managing user identities, access rights, and their own data governance","Securing the underlying operating system","Maintaining the physical facility"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Managing user identities, access rights, and their own data governance</strong> — even in SaaS the customer governs who accesses the service and how its data is classified and handled.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Patching the application code</b>: the SaaS provider maintains the application.</span><span class='qd'><b>Securing the underlying operating system</b>: managed by the provider in SaaS.</span><span class='qd'><b>Maintaining the physical facility</b>: always the provider's responsibility.</span>"},{"id":"D1-079","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"medium","q":"An assessor wants a framework that maps cloud controls across many standards and supports a public registry of provider assurance levels. Which CSA offering fits?","options":["The NIST Cybersecurity Framework tiers","The MITRE ATT&CK matrix","Cloud Controls Matrix (CCM) with the STAR registry","The OWASP Top Ten"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Cloud Controls Matrix (CCM) with the STAR registry</strong> — the CSA CCM maps cloud security controls across standards, and STAR is the public registry of provider assurance submissions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The NIST Cybersecurity Framework tiers</b>: a risk-management framework, not a cloud control mapping with a provider registry.</span><span class='qd'><b>The MITRE ATT&CK matrix</b>: catalogs adversary techniques, not a control assurance registry.</span><span class='qd'><b>The OWASP Top Ten</b>: a web-app risk list, not a cross-standard control matrix.</span>"},{"id":"D1-080","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"hard","q":"A hypervisor compromise could let an attacker escape a VM and reach neighboring tenants. Which control most directly mitigates this virtualization-layer threat?","options":["Enabling broader network access","Increasing VM density on each host","Sharing a single management account across tenants","Hardening and timely patching of the hypervisor with strong isolation"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Hardening and timely patching of the hypervisor with strong isolation</strong> — securing and patching the hypervisor and enforcing isolation reduces the risk of VM escape reaching other tenants.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Enabling broader network access</b>: increases exposure rather than mitigating escape risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing VM density on each host</b>: raises the impact of a single-host compromise.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sharing a single management account across tenants</b>: breaks isolation and creates a cross-tenant path.</span>"},{"id":"D1-081","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"medium","q":"Which statement best captures why data classification early in the secure data lifecycle strengthens later controls?","options":["Classification drives proportionate protection, handling, and retention decisions downstream","Classification eliminates the need for encryption","Classification is only relevant during the destroy phase","Classification replaces access control entirely"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Classification drives proportionate protection, handling, and retention decisions downstream</strong> — knowing sensitivity early lets each later phase apply the right level of control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Classification eliminates the need for encryption</b>: it informs encryption decisions, it does not replace them.</span><span class='qd'><b>Classification is only relevant during the destroy phase</b>: it matters across all phases, especially early.</span><span class='qd'><b>Classification replaces access control entirely</b>: classification complements, not replaces, access control.</span>"},{"id":"D1-082","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"easy","q":"When comparing candidate CSPs, why is verifying certifications against defined criteria preferable to accepting brand reputation?","options":["Reputation is legally enforceable","Certifications provide objective, auditable evidence against a standard","Certifications remove all residual risk","Reputation guarantees a specific SLA"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Certifications provide objective, auditable evidence against a standard</strong> — independent certifications give verifiable evidence tied to defined criteria, unlike subjective reputation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Reputation is legally enforceable</b>: reputation is not a contractual guarantee.</span><span class='qd'><b>Certifications remove all residual risk</b>: they reduce but never eliminate residual risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reputation guarantees a specific SLA</b>: SLAs come from contracts, not reputation.</span>"},{"id":"D1-083","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"An organization wants to prevent a compromised low-privilege account from escalating to administrative cloud actions. Which IAM design principle most directly addresses this?","options":["Assigning every user the same broad role","Disabling multi-factor authentication for admins","Privileged access management with separation of privileged and standard roles","Using a single shared admin login"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Privileged access management with separation of privileged and standard roles</strong> — isolating and tightly controlling privileged access limits how a compromised standard account can reach admin functions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Assigning every user the same broad role</b>: removes least privilege and enables escalation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling multi-factor authentication for admins</b>: weakens protection of the most sensitive accounts.</span><span class='qd'><b>Using a single shared admin login</b>: destroys accountability and centralizes risk.</span>"},{"id":"D1-084","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"hard","q":"A team designing a PaaS-hosted app must decide where its security responsibility clearly begins. Which layer is the customer most responsible for securing in PaaS?","options":["The runtime and middleware provided by the platform","The host operating system","The physical and virtualization infrastructure","The application code and its data"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The application code and its data</strong> — in PaaS the provider manages the platform, runtime, and OS, while the customer secures the code they deploy and the data it handles.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The runtime and middleware provided by the platform</b>: managed by the PaaS provider.</span><span class='qd'><b>The host operating system</b>: abstracted and managed by the provider in PaaS.</span><span class='qd'><b>The physical and virtualization infrastructure</b>: always the provider's responsibility.</span>"},{"id":"D1-085","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"easy","q":"Which media-sanitization method is generally impractical for a cloud customer using object storage, and why?","options":["Physical destruction, because the customer does not control the media","Cryptographic erasure, because keys cannot be deleted","Overwriting, because the API forbids writes","Logical deletion, because it is not supported"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Physical destruction, because the customer does not control the media</strong> — customers lack access to provider-owned physical media, so physical destruction is not a customer-executable option.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cryptographic erasure, because keys cannot be deleted</b>: keys generally can be deleted, making crypto-erasure viable.</span><span class='qd'><b>Overwriting, because the API forbids writes</b>: writes are normally allowed; the real limit is reaching all physical copies.</span><span class='qd'><b>Logical deletion, because it is not supported</b>: logical deletion is supported but may not guarantee unrecoverability.</span>"},{"id":"D1-086","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"medium","q":"A customer needs assurance about the design and operating effectiveness of a CSP's security controls over a period, for restricted internal use by auditors. Which report best meets this?","options":["SOC 3","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 1 Type II","Common Criteria certificate"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>SOC 2 Type II</strong> — SOC 2 Type II reports on both design and operating effectiveness of security-relevant controls over a period, for restricted audiences.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 3</b>: a public summary without detailed control testing over a period for auditors.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 1 Type II</b>: focuses on controls relevant to financial reporting, not general security trust criteria.</span><span class='qd'><b>Common Criteria certificate</b>: evaluates a product, not a service organization's operating controls.</span>"},{"id":"D1-087","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"hard","q":"An architect must justify a hybrid design where regulated data stays in a private cloud while burst compute runs in public cloud. Which secure-design driver most strongly supports this split?","options":["Maximizing vendor lock-in intentionally","Eliminating all encryption needs","Meeting data-residency and sovereignty requirements while retaining elasticity","Guaranteeing zero shared responsibility"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Meeting data-residency and sovereignty requirements while retaining elasticity</strong> — keeping regulated data private satisfies residency/sovereignty, while public burst preserves elasticity, a classic hybrid rationale.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Maximizing vendor lock-in intentionally</b>: lock-in is a risk to avoid, not a design driver.</span><span class='qd'><b>Eliminating all encryption needs</b>: hybrid does not remove encryption requirements.</span><span class='qd'><b>Guaranteeing zero shared responsibility</b>: shared responsibility always applies in cloud.</span>"},{"id":"D1-088","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"Which threat is most characteristic of multi-tenant cloud environments and is mitigated primarily through strong logical isolation and access controls?","options":["Physical theft of a laptop","Local power surge in a home office","Paper document loss","Cross-tenant data leakage"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Cross-tenant data leakage</strong> — sharing infrastructure among tenants creates the risk of one tenant reaching another's data, mitigated by strong logical isolation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical theft of a laptop</b>: an endpoint risk, not specific to multi-tenancy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Local power surge in a home office</b>: an environmental issue unrelated to tenant isolation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Paper document loss</b>: a physical records risk, not a cloud multi-tenancy threat.</span>"},{"id":"D1-089","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"medium","q":"During which secure-data-lifecycle phase is data most exposed because it must be decrypted for processing, warranting controls like TEEs or strict memory protections?","options":["Use","Store","Archive","Destroy"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Use</strong> — data in use is decrypted in memory for processing, making it the most exposed phase and the target of protections like trusted execution environments.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Store</b>: at rest, data can remain encrypted, so exposure is lower.</span><span class='qd'><b>Archive</b>: archived data is typically encrypted and offline, lower exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Destroy</b>: the goal here is unrecoverability, not active processing exposure.</span>"},{"id":"D1-090","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"hard","q":"An evaluator finds a CSP holds ISO/IEC 27001 but the certificate's scope statement excludes the specific managed service the customer will use. What is the correct conclusion?","options":["The certificate automatically covers all services","The certification does not assure the in-scope service; verify scope alignment","Scope statements are irrelevant to assurance","The customer inherits full compliance regardless of scope"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The certification does not assure the in-scope service; verify scope alignment</strong> — a certificate only attests to what its scope covers, so an excluded service is not assured and scope must be verified.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The certificate automatically covers all services</b>: certificates are bounded by their scope statement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Scope statements are irrelevant to assurance</b>: scope is precisely what defines the assurance boundary.</span><span class='qd'><b>The customer inherits full compliance regardless of scope</b>: inheritance is limited to in-scope, attested controls.</span>"},{"id":"D1-091","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"easy","q":"Which practice ensures that new cloud instances start from a known-good, hardened configuration rather than drifting into insecure states?","options":["Manually configuring each server by hand","Disabling configuration management","Baselining from a hardened golden image","Allowing unrestricted local changes"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Baselining from a hardened golden image</strong> — provisioning from a hardened baseline image ensures consistent, known-good security posture at launch.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Manually configuring each server by hand</b>: invites inconsistency and human error.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling configuration management</b>: removes the mechanism that prevents drift.</span><span class='qd'><b>Allowing unrestricted local changes</b>: causes configuration drift and weakens security.</span>"},{"id":"D1-092","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"medium","q":"An architect wants BC/DR that leverages cloud elasticity so recovery capacity is provisioned automatically when a region fails. Which cloud characteristic makes this efficient compared to traditional DR?","options":["Fixed capacity planning years in advance","Manual hardware procurement per event","Static single-region deployment","Rapid elasticity with on-demand self-service"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Rapid elasticity with on-demand self-service</strong> — cloud can provision recovery capacity on demand during a failover, avoiding pre-purchased idle hardware.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Fixed capacity planning years in advance</b>: the traditional model elasticity replaces.</span><span class='qd'><b>Manual hardware procurement per event</b>: slow and defeats on-demand recovery.</span><span class='qd'><b>Static single-region deployment</b>: offers no cross-region recovery capacity.</span>"},{"id":"D1-093","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"medium","q":"A regulated customer requires that a CSP's cryptographic module used for key storage be validated to a government-recognized level. Which requirement should appear in the RFP?","options":["FIPS 140-3 validation of the HSM/key store module","A vendor blog post about encryption","An internal wiki page on ciphers","A generic statement that 'data is encrypted'"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>FIPS 140-3 validation of the HSM/key store module</strong> — FIPS 140-3 is the recognized validation for cryptographic modules and is the appropriate, verifiable RFP requirement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A vendor blog post about encryption</b>: unverified marketing, not validation.</span><span class='qd'><b>An internal wiki page on ciphers</b>: internal documentation, not independent validation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A generic statement that 'data is encrypted'</b>: vague and unverifiable at the module level.</span>"},{"id":"D1-094","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"hard","q":"An architect needs to guarantee that traffic between microservices carries mutual authentication and encryption without trusting the underlying network. Which approach best embodies zero-trust service-to-service security?","options":["An open flat network relying on the VPC boundary","Mutual TLS with per-service identities enforced regardless of network location","Plaintext internal traffic assumed safe inside the perimeter","IP allow-lists as the sole authentication mechanism"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Mutual TLS with per-service identities enforced regardless of network location</strong> — mTLS with strong per-service identity authenticates and encrypts each call without trusting the network, the essence of zero trust for services.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>An open flat network relying on the VPC boundary</b>: trusts the network, contradicting zero trust.</span><span class='qd'><b>Plaintext internal traffic assumed safe inside the perimeter</b>: assumes implicit trust and exposes data.</span><span class='qd'><b>IP allow-lists as the sole authentication mechanism</b>: IPs are spoofable and are not strong identity.</span>"},{"id":"D1-095","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"medium","q":"Why is defining data-handling and deletion responsibilities per service category (IaaS, PaaS, SaaS) essential to secure cloud design?","options":["Because deletion is identical across all models","Because the provider always deletes everything automatically","Because the shared-responsibility split changes what the customer must control by model","Because customers never handle data in any model"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Because the shared-responsibility split changes what the customer must control by model</strong> — responsibility for data handling and deletion shifts across IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS, so it must be defined per model.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Because deletion is identical across all models</b>: it differs; the customer's control varies by model.</span><span class='qd'><b>Because the provider always deletes everything automatically</b>: customers retain deletion duties, especially for their data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Because customers never handle data in any model</b>: customers govern their data in every model.</span>"},{"id":"D1-096","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"easy","q":"What is the main value of the CSA STAR registry to an organization evaluating providers?","options":["It sells cloud services directly","It replaces the need for any contract","It guarantees the lowest price","It offers a central place to review providers' self-assessments and third-party attestations"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>It offers a central place to review providers' self-assessments and third-party attestations</strong> — STAR centralizes provider assurance submissions so evaluators can compare posture.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It sells cloud services directly</b>: STAR is a registry, not a marketplace.</span><span class='qd'><b>It replaces the need for any contract</b>: contracts remain necessary for obligations and SLAs.</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees the lowest price</b>: STAR addresses assurance, not pricing.</span>"},{"id":"D1-097","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"hard","q":"A team weighs adopting a portable container-and-orchestration approach versus a provider's proprietary managed service. Which trade-off most accurately frames the secure-design decision?","options":["Portability and reduced lock-in versus deeper provider integration and convenience","More lock-in but guaranteed lower risk","Loss of interoperability but improved reversibility","Elimination of shared responsibility either way"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Portability and reduced lock-in versus deeper provider integration and convenience</strong> — portable containers reduce lock-in and aid reversibility, while proprietary managed services offer convenience at the cost of dependency; that is the core trade-off.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>More lock-in but guaranteed lower risk</b>: lock-in is a risk, not a risk reducer.</span><span class='qd'><b>Loss of interoperability but improved reversibility</b>: portability improves both interoperability and reversibility, so this mischaracterizes it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Elimination of shared responsibility either way</b>: shared responsibility persists in both choices.</span>"},{"id":"D1-098","domain":1,"obj":"1.3","diff":"medium","q":"An organization wants a single mechanism to enforce consistent identity, authentication, and authorization for human, privileged, and service access across cloud resources. Which capability best centralizes this?","options":["Per-application local password files","A centralized IAM system with role-based policies and MFA","Individually managed static keys per team","Ad hoc access granted verbally by managers"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A centralized IAM system with role-based policies and MFA</strong> — centralized IAM enforces consistent authentication and authorization across all identity types with policy and MFA.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Per-application local password files</b>: fragmented, inconsistent, and hard to govern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Individually managed static keys per team</b>: creates sprawl and weak accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ad hoc access granted verbally by managers</b>: unauditable and inconsistent.</span>"},{"id":"D1-099","domain":1,"obj":"1.4","diff":"hard","q":"A DevOps team wants security controls to be codified and versioned so every deployment is repeatably compliant and drift is detectable. Which secure-design practice achieves this?","options":["Manual checklists reviewed occasionally","Undocumented tribal knowledge","Policy-as-code and infrastructure-as-code with automated compliance checks","One-time hardening never revisited"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Policy-as-code and infrastructure-as-code with automated compliance checks</strong> — codifying policy and infrastructure makes security repeatable, versioned, and continuously verifiable, detecting drift automatically.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Manual checklists reviewed occasionally</b>: not repeatable or automated, and drift goes unnoticed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Undocumented tribal knowledge</b>: not codified, versioned, or auditable.</span><span class='qd'><b>One-time hardening never revisited</b>: cannot detect or correct later drift.</span>"},{"id":"D1-100","domain":1,"obj":"1.5","diff":"medium","q":"An assessor must judge whether a provider's audit report is relevant to the customer's use case. Which factor most affects that relevance?","options":["The font used in the report","The length of the executive summary","The provider's social media following","Whether the report's scope covers the specific services and controls the customer will rely on"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Whether the report's scope covers the specific services and controls the customer will rely on</strong> — an audit report is only relevant insofar as its scope includes the services and controls the customer actually depends on.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The font used in the report</b>: cosmetic and irrelevant to assurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The length of the executive summary</b>: length does not determine scope relevance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The provider's social media following</b>: popularity is unrelated to audit scope or assurance.</span>"}]);
